In article &lt;11481@s.ms.uky.edu&gt;, david@ms (David Herron -- One of the vertebrae) writes:
&gt;To have the answers a master nameserver for a domain vary
&gt;depending on who is asking the question?

Well, since you have several nameservers that should keep identical
information, they all should have the same value.  I could ask any of
them and get the same results.  Asking the name servers to perform
additional overhead to make my life easier doesn't seem polite.

&gt;But for one on the local net I may want to either not return an MX
&gt;record or return one *only* listing the given host, or a list like
&gt;above but headed by the given host and not containing the questioning host.

This is a different case. You may want to have an unpublished nameserver
on some machine on your local net. The local machines would you this one,
while the rest of the world would use the well known nameserver.

Apparently name service doesn't have any concept of "perspective".
But the machine requesting service could use the MX preferences
along with knowledge of the network and past experience to pick the
best machine to forward to.

Perhaps someone could hack the name server to give different values
to a different (local) network?

--
